    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "riLMiV5muCwP"
      },
      "source": [
        "## **1**.&nbsp; **Why do we need Classes?**"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "q-HpDsdyzEb3"
      },
      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# **1. Why Do We Need Classes?**\n",
        "\n",
        "One of the biggest challenges in programming is managing complexity. Object-oriented programming addresses this by letting you bundle **data** (attributes) and **behaviour** (methods) into cohesive units that represent real-world or conceptual entities.\n",
        "\n",
        "1. [Python Crash Course](https://learning.oreilly.com/library/view/python-crash-course/9781098156664/).\n",
        "2. [Python in a Nutshell ch. 4](https://learning.oreilly.com/library/view/python-in-a/9781098113544/ch04.html#descriptors)."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "XIpWvbrOuO_b"
      },
      "source": [
        "## **2**.&nbsp; **Define a Class; Instance vs Class Attributes**"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "srngVWv8FV1C"
      },
      "source": [
        "A *class* in Python serves as a blueprint for creating objects, also known as *instances*. When you call a class like a function, it instantiates an object of that type. Each class can have attributes—variables bound to the class or its instances—that store data or define behavior through methods. Additionally, a class can inherit from other classes, allowing it to reuse and extend existing functionality. In essence, **a class provides a structured way to define and organise related data and behaviors, guiding how its instances are created and interact**."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "id": "SaieZpcuCQy5"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "cellView": "form",
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "mB-cHX5768Ao",
        "outputId": "db3e2365-6344-4c79-de07-0139dd4fa411"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# @title Example class definiton\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Class attribute: shared by ALL instances\n",
        "    instance_count = 0\n",
        "\n",
        "    def __init__(self, party, age):\n",
        "        # Instance attributes: unique to EACH instance\n",
        "        self.party = party\n",
        "        self.age = age\n",
        "        self.name = \"generic_name\"\n",
        "        Politician.instance_count += 1   # update the shared counter\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create two instances\n",
        "p1 = Politician(\"Labour\", 42)\n",
        "p2 = Politician(\"Conservative\", 55)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Access instance attributes\n",
        "print(p1.party, p1.age)        # Labour 42\n",
        "print(p2.party, p2.age)        # Conservative 55\n",
        "\n",
        "# Access class attribute (same for both)\n",
        "print(Politician.instance_count)  # 2\n",
        "print(p1.instance_count)          # 2 (looked up via the class)\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "> **Tip:** While you *can* add attributes outside of `__init__()`, initialising everything inside it keeps your class readable and predictable.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### A note on naming conventions\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Class names** use CamelCase: `Politician`, `DataLoader`, `ElectionResult`\n",
        "- **Instance and variable names** use snake_case: `my_politician`, `vote_count`\n",
        "- **Every class should have a docstring** immediately after the class definition\n",
        "- Use one blank line between methods within a class, two blank lines between classes\n",
        "\n",
        "See the [PEP 8 Style Guide](https://peps.python.org/pep-0008/) for the full conventions.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### ✏️ **Exercise 1: Classes and Attributes**\n",
        "\n",
        "**1a)** Create a `Country` class with instance attributes `name`, `population` (in millions), and `region`. Add a docstring.\n",
        "\n",
        "**1b)** Create three `Country` instances: the UK, France, and Brazil. Print each country's name and population.\n",
        "\n",
        "**1c)** Add a **class attribute** `country_count` that tracks how many `Country` instances have been created (increment it in `__init__`). Print `Country.country_count` after creating your three countries.\n",
        "\n",
        "**1d)** Use `type()` and `isinstance()` to verify that your objects are `Country` instances.\n",
        "\n",
        "**⭐ Extra:** Create a class `Team` with a class attribute `members = []`. In `__init__`, append a new member name to `members`. Create three teams and print `Team.members`. What happens? Why is this a problem? Fix it so each instance has its own list.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# Exercise 1: Your code here\n",
        "\n",
