    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "SbhqXWalB58J"
      },
      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# **4. Inheritance**\n",
        "\n",
        "When one class **inherits** from another, it takes on the parent's attributes and methods. The child class can then add new functionality or **override** existing methods.\n",
        "\n",
        "- If you need to import a module from the standard library and a module that you wrote, place the import statement for the standard library module first. Then add a blank line and the import statement for the module you wrote. In programs with multiple import statements, this convention makes it easier to see where the different modules used in the program come from.\n",
        "\n",
        "Source: [Python Crash Course](https://learning.oreilly.com/library/view/python-crash-course/9781098156664/).\n",
        "See also: [PEP8 Style Guide for Python Code](https://peps.python.org/pep-0008/).\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "2bdDwDGxuZoN"
      },
      "source": [
        "## **3**.&nbsp; **Methods and Special Methods**"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "5mPUormLP3b1"
      },
      "source": [
        "In Python, **methods are functions that belong to a class and operate on its instances**. They allow objects to interact with their data and perform actions. There are two key types of methods:\n",
        "- **regular methods**, which explicitly define behavior.\n",
        "- **special methods**, which enable built-in operations and object customisation.\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "IuqHMwba-SSa"
      },
      "source": [
        "### **The `__init__()` Method**\n",
        "\n",
        "The `__init__()` method (pronounced \"dunder init\", short for double underscore init) is a special method that performs instance initialisation. Its primary role is to bind attributes to a newly created instance. The double underscores in `__init__` prevent name conflicts with Pythonss built-in identifiers.\n",
        "\n",
        "The first parameter of `__init__()` must always be self, which represents the instance being created. When an object is instantiated, Python automatically calls `__init__()`, passing the new instance as self. This ensures that each instance has its own independent attributes.\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "id": "5B8hFilU9mbp"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "class Politician:\n",
        "    \"\"\"Base class for politicians.\"\"\"\n",
        "\n",
        "    def __init__(self, party, age):\n",
        "        self.party = party\n",
        "        self.age = age\n",
        "\n",
        "    def make_speech(self):\n",
        "        print(f\"Vote for {self.party}!\")\n",
        "\n",
        "    def __str__(self):\n",
        "        return f\"Politician(party={self.party}, age={self.age})\"\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "class President(Politician):\n",
        "    \"\"\"A president inherits from Politician and adds tenure tracking.\"\"\"\n",
        "\n",
        "    def __init__(self, party, age, country):\n",
        "        super().__init__(party, age)    # call the parent's __init__\n",
        "        self.country = country\n",
        "        self.tenure = 0\n",
        "\n",
        "    def make_policy(self):\n",
        "        return f\"President of {self.country} signed a new policy.\"\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "pres = President(\"Democrats\", 81, \"USA\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Inherited from Politician\n",
        "pres.make_speech()         # Vote for Democrats!\n",
        "print(pres.party)          # Democrats\n",
        "\n",
        "# New in President\n",
        "print(pres.make_policy())  # President of USA signed a new policy.\n",
        "print(pres.country)        # USA\n",
        "\n",
        "# isinstance checks\n",
        "print(isinstance(pres, President))    # True\n",
        "print(isinstance(pres, Politician))   # True (a President IS a Politician)\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### The `super()` function\n",
        "\n",
        "The `super()` function calls a method from the parent class. It is most commonly used in `__init__()` to ensure the parent's setup logic runs before the child adds its own attributes.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Overriding methods\n",
        "\n",
        "To change a parent method's behaviour, define a method with the same name in the child class. Python will use the child's version:\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "class President(Politician):\n",
        "    \"\"\"A president with an overridden __str__.\"\"\"\n",
        "\n",
        "    def __init__(self, party, age, country):\n",
        "        super().__init__(party, age)\n",
        "        self.country = country\n",
        "\n",
        "    def __str__(self):\n",
        "        # Override the parent's __str__\n",
        "        return f\"President of {self.country} ({self.party}, age {self.age})\"\n",
        "\n",
        "    def make_speech(self):\n",
        "        # Override the parent's make_speech\n",
        "        print(f\"As President of {self.country}, I promise to lead!\")\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "pres = President(\"Democrats\", 81, \"USA\")\n",
        "print(pres)          # President of USA (Democrats, age 81)\n",
        "pres.make_speech()   # As President of USA, I promise to lead!\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### ✏️ **Exercise 3: Inheritance**\n",
        "\n",
        "**3a)** Create a `PrimeMinister` class that inherits from `Politician`. Its `__init__` should accept `party`, `age`, and `country`, and call `super().__init__()` for `party` and `age`.\n",
        "\n",
        "**3b)** Add a `call_election()` method to `PrimeMinister` that prints something like `\"PM of UK calls a general election!\"`.\n",
        "\n",
        "**3c)** Override `__str__()` in `PrimeMinister` to return `\"PM of UK (Labour, age 42)\"`.\n",
        "\n",
        "**3d)** Create a list containing both `Politician` and `PrimeMinister` instances. Loop over them and call `make_speech()` on each. Notice how both types respond, even though they may have different implementations.\n",
        "\n",
        "**⭐ Extra:** Override `make_speech()` in `PrimeMinister` so it first calls the parent's version (using `super().make_speech()`) and then adds a line about governing.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# Exercise 3: Your code here\n",
        "\n",
        "# 3a)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "# 3b)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "# 3c)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "# 3d)\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# **5. Composition**\n",
        "\n",
        "Composition models \"has-a\" relationships: instead of inheriting, one class **contains instances of another** as attributes.\n",
        "\n",
        "This is useful when objects work together but aren't variations of the same thing. A Parliament **has** Politicians (it is not *a type of* Politician). A Car **has** an Engine.\n",
        "\n",
        "| Relationship | Pattern | Example |\n",
        "|------|------|-------|\n",
        "| \"is-a\" | Inheritance | President **is a** Politician |\n",
        "| \"has-a\" | Composition | Parliament **has** Politicians |\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "class Party:\n",
        "    \"\"\"A political party with a policy position.\"\"\"\n",
        "\n",
        "    def __init__(self, name, policy_preference):\n",
        "        self.name = name\n",
        "        self.policy_preference = policy_preference\n",
        "\n",
        "    def __str__(self):\n",
        "        return f\"Party({self.name})\"\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "class Politician:\n",
        "    \"\"\"A politician who belongs to a party (composition).\"\"\"\n",
        "\n",
        "    def __init__(self, age, party):\n",
        "        self.age = age # instance attribute\n",
        "        self.party = party # instance attribute\n",
        "\n",
        "p1 = Politician(35, \"A\") # __init__() is called automatically"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Sty-NJin-xqm"
      },
      "source": [
        "While instance attributes are usually bound in `__init__()`, you can modify or add attributes outside of it. However, initialising all attributes in `__init__()` improves readability and ensures consistency.\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "qK0kf4gE-7oq"
      },
      "source": [
        "### **Special Methods `__method__()`**\n",
        "\n",
        "Python provides a set of predefined special methods (also known as dunder methods, short for double underscore methods). These methods enable classes to integrate with Pythonss built-in operations. Special methods are automatically called when their corresponding operations are used.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example:\n",
        "\n",
        "- `__str__()` defines how an instance is represented as a string `str(obj)` or `print(obj)`.\n",
        "- `__len__()` allows an instance to be used with `len()`.\n",
        "- `__call__()` makes an instance callable like a function."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "juR7QS9i9nIC",
        "outputId": "c19e84e2-1ebc-4e2a-c871-af23c064e5b6"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "class Politician:\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    Defines politician attributes and behaviours.\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "\n",
        "    instance_count = 0\n",
        "\n",
        "    def __init__(self, party, age):\n",
        "        self.party = party\n",
        "        self.age = age\n",
        "        self.party = party       # party is a Party instance\n",
        "        self.vote = False\n",
        "\n",
        "    def cast_vote(self, proposition):\n",
        "        \"\"\"Vote yes if the proposition matches the party's preference.\"\"\"\n",
        "        if proposition == self.party.policy_preference:\n",
        "            self.vote = True\n",
        "\n",
