        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# **6. Modules and Importing** (Demo)\n",
        "\n",
        "A **module** in Python is simply a `.py` file containing definitions (functions, classes, variables) that you can **reuse** in other programs.\n",
        "\n",
        "By splitting code into modules, you make it easier to organise, test, and maintain larger projects. Import styles:\n",
        "\n",
        "```python\n",
        "import politics as pcs             # import the whole module under an alias\n",
        "from politics import Politician    # import a specific class\n",
        "from politics import *             # import everything (not recommended)\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "This modular approach, combined with OOP, is what makes Python so powerful for building both small scripts and large-scale applications.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "If we saved all our classes from this session into a file called `politics.py`, we could use them like this:\n"
      ]
